    "texts": [
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Identification features",
            "shortText": "<p>Dorsally flattened with eight shell plates articulating on its dorsal side, surrounded by a soft fleshy girdle. Wide girdle covered with brownish clear, straight spines at the top margin, and smaller ones pressed together at the bottom, making this species easily distinguishable. When turned over, gills extend halfway along the foot. Middle plates sharpen to the hind margin. Texture of shell centrally with radial ribs and with flattened granules on the sides. Colour light beige with brown on small shell plates. Articulamentum whitish pink and with a slight gap between the two anterior shell extensions.&nbsp;</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_1_5421",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Adult size",
            "shortText": "<p>Small, typically around 5-10 mm total body length.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_2_5422",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Distribution",
            "shortText": "<p><u>Global:</u> Endemic to South Africa.</p><p><u>Local/Regional:</u> Melkbosstrand to Bhanga Nek.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_3_5423",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Biology",
            "shortText": "<p>Between rocks and crevices in the<strong> </strong>Intertidal zone, discrete and camouflaged, never exposed.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_4_5424",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Food / prey",
            "shortText": "<p>Herbivorous - radula rasping algae off the rocks.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_5_5425",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Reproduction",
            "shortText": "<p>External fertilization releasing eggs and sperm into the water. Eggs develop into planktonic trochohore larvae that settle as metamorphosized juvenile chitons.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_6_5426",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Similar species",
            "shortText": "<p>The related<strong> </strong><i>A. garnoti </i>occurs from Saldanha Bay to Southern KwaZulu-Natal and has much shorter and bent tuft spines and marginal fringe spines. Granules on shell of <i>A. variegata </i>are flatter and more spread out than in <i>A. garnoti. </i>Less common.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_7_5427",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Further reading / References",
            "shortText": "Ashby, E (1928). South African chitons, being a description of the Polyplacophora represented in the Turton Collection. <i>Proceedings of the Malacological Society of London</i>, 18 (2), 76-92. (p. 79, pl. 6, figs 1-4 as <i>Acanthochiton tortoni</i>).<br><br>Els, M & Els, R  (2022).On the variegata trail: finding a cryptic South African chiton beauty: <i>Acanthochitona variegata</i>.<br><br>Nierstrasz, HF (1906). Beiträge zur Kenntnis der Fauna von Süd-Afrika. VI. Chitonen aus der Kapkololonie [sic] und Natal. <i>Zoologische Jahrbücher, Abteilung für Systematik, Geographie und Biologie der Tiere</i>, 23, 487–520.",
